		<header>
			
			<h1>EC proposals for CFP external dimension reform launched</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 August 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 13 July 2011, the EC launched a package of proposals for the reform of the Common Fisheries Policy (CFP). Both the general legislative proposal for the CFP – often referred to as the ‘basic regulation’ – and the EC communication on the external dimension of the CFP, deal with fisheries agreements and EU participation in international forums and in regional fisheries management organisations (RFMOs).</p><p>The basic regulation details specific objectives for EU participation in international fisheries organisations (IFOs) and for sustainable fisheries agreements (SFAs, to replace FPAs). Concerning SFAs, the proposal spells out that SFAs ‘with third countries shall establish a legal, economic and environmental governance framework for fishing activities carried out by Union fishing vessels in third-country waters’. Moreover, ‘Union fishing vessels shall catch only surplus of the allowable catch determined by the third country as referred to in article 62(2) of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, and identified on the basis of the best scientific advice and relevant information exchanged between the union and the third country concerned about the total fishing effort on the affected stocks, in order to ensure that fishery resources remain above levels capable of producing maximum sustainable yield’. Financial assistance shall be provided to third countries through SFAs in order to ‘support part of the cost of access to the fisheries resources in third-country waters and establish the governance framework, including the development and maintenance of the necessary scientific and research institutions, monitoring, control and surveillance capability and other capacity-building items pertaining to the development of a sustainable fisheries policy driven by the third country. Such financial assistance shall be conditioned upon the achievement of specific results’. Finally, when looking at financial instruments, the proposal specifies that EU financial assistance towards member states and operators ‘shall be conditional upon compliance with the rules of the CFP’.</p><p>The EC <i>Communication</i> on the external dimension details the future principles, approach and main actions that will be taken by the Commission, to address a variety of issues in international forums, RFMOs, and in bilateral SFAs. In international forums, the EC proposes specifically to launch discussions with other major fishery market states, like the USA and Japan, <i>‘</i>to implement a common approach for preventing IUU products from entering these markets’; and to launch ‘a high-level political initiative to discuss the avenues for capacity reduction on a global level’.</p><p>At the level of RFMOs, the EC proposals include the promotion of the concept of a pay-for-access regime through the introduction of fees for placing vessels on RFMO lists of authorised vessels.</p><p>For future fisheries agreements, the EC will propose to ‘decouple sectoral support from payments-for-access rights and to define the former in the light of the needs and absorption capacity of partner countries in fisheries governance; seek to introduce stronger conditionality into the payment of sectoral support, so that no payment will be made without a guarantee of result’.</p><p>A final chapter is devoted to ‘Coherence with other policies’, which states that ‘Coordination of fisheries and development policies should ensure that the recognition of the aspirations of the developing states to build up their own fishery sector is linked to raising awareness of their duties of sustainable fisheries governance’. In particular, the EC will develop and implement ocean- and sea-based regional strategies for sustainable fisheries, e.g. in the Pacific and Indian Oceans.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>‘Proposal for a Regulation of the European Parliament and of the Council on the Common Fisheries Policy’, 13 July 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/reform/com_2011_425_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/reform/com_2011_425_en.pdf</a></p><p>‘Communication from the Commission to the European Parliament, the Council, the European Economic and Social Committee and the Committee of the Regions on External Dimension of the Common Fisheries Policy’, 13 July 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/reform/com_2011_424_en.pdf" target="_self">http://ec.europa.eu/fisheries/reform/com_2011_424_en.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The concerns for coherence, as highlighted in the EC proposals, are to be welcomed, especially ‘horizontal coherence’ with other EU policies (including development policies), which provides a basis for developing specific strategies and mechanisms to ensure a dialogue with ACP countries. The concern for coherence in trade policy, which will become particularly important as the EU is striving to ensure that in the future all EU-consumed products will come from sustainable sources, is also to be welcomed. The concern for ‘vertical coherence’ also needs noting, regarding initiatives taken at international, regional and bilateral level. Two aspects of this are particularly important: the fights against IUU fishing and against global over-capacity, two issues that particularly affect ACP countries. It is therefore important that ACP countries engage with the EU on these three aspects of coherence so as to develop a dialogue and joint action.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
